If you use a library like Springdoc or Springfox, you can define an  [`OpenAPI`](https://javadoc.io/doc/io.swagger.core.v3/swagger-models/latest/io/swagger/v3/oas/models/OpenAPI.html) bean:

```java
@Bean
public OpenAPI openAPI() {
    return new OpenAPI()
        .servers(List.of(
            new Server().url(&quot;http://my-url&quot;)
        ))
        // ... Rest of configuration
}
```

All the configuration you put in the `@OpenApiDefinition` annotation, can also be put within this object.

This also allows you to configure the URL (and other properties) through properties. For example:

```java
@Bean
public OpenAPI openAPI(@Value(&quot;${openapi.server}&quot;) String server) {
    return new OpenAPI()
        .servers(List.of(
            new Server().url(server)
        ))
        // ... Rest of configuration
}
```

One way to avoid this, is by print the logs of the tomcat from warning severity,

you can give a try with in your application.properties


&#39;logging.level.org.apache.catalina.core.*=WARN&#39;
instead of &#39;logging.level.org.apache=DEBUG&#39;

