However, the code `DBHelper.AAAA1.equals(&quot;test111&quot;)` and also ` (DBHelper.BBBB1.equals(&quot;test222&quot;))` will always be false.

- `DBhelper.AAAA1` hold the value **`AAAA1`** it will never be &quot;test111&quot; (likewise for BBBB1). 

    - AAA1 can never change as it is final, there is just the one occurrence for however many instances of DBHelper exist.

At a guess it would appear that you want to set the value displayed by the Text_test view to a value from the database.

So it would appear that you want to extract some data from one or both of the tables and test that to see if it is test111 and/or test222.

To extract data you typically use the SQLiteDatabase [**`Query`*][1]* method which returns a Cursor, which will contain 0-n rows.

- You may want to use/code `Cursor csr = db.query(DBHelper.AAAA,null,null,null,null,null,null);`

and then loop through the cursor or perhaps just look at the first row in the  cursor. so respectively either

    while(csr.moveToNext()) {....}
or

    if (csr.moveToFirst()) {...}

A cursor&#39;s row will have columns, those depending upon the columns that are extracted as per the 2nd parameter passed that is either **columns**, String[], where the each element is a column name (or expression) **OR** **`null`**. Null equates to the SQLite *, which stands for all columns (in your case all columns is just the 1 column, so null is simple).

So after a move????, if the move can be undertaken then true will be returned, if the move could not be undertaken (e.g. empty cursor, end of cursor) then false is returned. hence the while loop (for all rows) and the if for just the first row. Additionally the cursor will be positioned at the row.

You can then extract data from the column(s), you access a column according to it&#39;s offset. So the first column is at offset 0, the second at 1 ....

So to get the value from the first column you can use a `get????` method, where ???? is the type of the data. You want a String value so the `getString` method is apt. So you could have:-

