There are several ways to remove the final line separator from the string returned by method `getRectangle`.

One way &amp;ndash; that minimizes the required changes to your code &amp;ndash; is to simply remove the final line separator before returning the value. Again, there are several ways to do this, for example:
```java
rectangle.substring(0, rectangle.lastIndexOf(System.lineSeparator()))
```
Refer to the *javadoc* for class [StringBuilder][1].

Here is method `getRectangle` with the above change.
```java
public static String getRectangle(int maxRows, int maxCols, char symbol) {
    if (maxRows &lt; 1 || maxCols &lt; 1) {
        return null;
    }
    StringBuilder rectangle = new StringBuilder();
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; maxRows; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j &lt; maxCols; j++) {
            rectangle.append(symbol);
        }
        rectangle.append(System.lineSeparator());
    }
    return rectangle.substring(0, rectangle.lastIndexOf(System.lineSeparator()));
}
```
Alternatively, you can change the logic of your nested `for` loops. Instead of appending a line separator, prepend it for every line except for the first line, as demonstrated in the below `getOblong` method.
```java
public static String getOblong(int maxRows, int maxCols, char symbol) {
    boolean first = true;
    StringBuilder rectangle = new StringBuilder();
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; maxRows; i++) {
        if (first) {
            first = false;
        }
        else {
            rectangle.append(System.lineSeparator());
        }
        for (int j = 0; j &lt; maxCols; j++) {
            rectangle.append(symbol);
        }
    }
    return rectangle.toString();
}
```
Actually, you don&#39;t need to use loops as there are already API methods that achieve the same result, as demonstrated in the below `getRect` method:
```java
public static String getRect(int rows, int cols, char symbol) {
    String s = String.valueOf(symbol);
    String line = s.repeat(cols);
    String[] lines = new String[rows];
    java.util.Arrays.fill(lines, line);
    return String.join(System.lineSeparator(), lines);
}
```
Again, refer to *javadoc* for class [String][2].

By the way, since you are already checking validity of parameters `maxRows` and `maxCols`, in your `getRectangle` method, shouldn&#39;t you also check whether `symbol` is a [printable character][3]?


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/StringBuilder.html
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/21/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html
  [3]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/220547/printable-char-in-java

